{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9184c6f0b6211c49", "type": "tool_result", "content": "on the model on the question so that both feature extraction and fusion remain text-guided. Co-attention and question-guided fusion from VQA (e.g., [ MCAN , HCAttn , PSAC ] ) inspire AVQA systems that ground sounding regions and fuse audio–visual cues under textual guidance (e.g., [ MUSIC-AVQA , COCA , APL ] ). Recent work further strengthens conditioning via prompt reformulation or question-aware experts: TSPM turns questions into declaratives to align with visual semantics before temporal/spatial selection [ TSPM ] , and [ QATIGER ] introduces question-aware Gaussian experts. Dialog-style conditioning also appears in scene-aware settings [ AVSD ] . Overall, these methods filter modalities through question semantics to suppress irrelevant content and to guide cross-modal reasoning [ TSPM , MUSIC-AVQA , LAVISH ] . 2.2 Spatial Perception Another line of work localizes question-relevant regions and sound sources, often by coupling detection with cross-modal grounding. Panoramic grounding requires spherical spatial reasoning in 360° videos [ PANO-AVQA ] . Progressive pipelines (e.g., PSTP-Net) first select key segments and then pick relevant patches with audio-guided visual attention [ PSTP-NET ] . Complementary strategies include object-aware learning [ APL ] , causal regularization against spurious cues [ COCA ] , and parameter-efficient ViT-based learners [ LAVISH ] . In practice, many approaches pair these spatial modules with question-aware fusion to maintain textual guidance throughout [ MUSIC-AVQA , TSPM ] . 2.3 Temporal Perception Temporal perception targets frames or segments that matter for the question, ensuring that evidence is aggregated over the correct intervals. PSTP-Net explicitly performs segment selection before spatial filtering [ PSTP-NET ] , while TSPM adds a prompt-guided temporal module [ TSPM ] . Earlier video-/audio-QA studies explore temporal reasoning with recurrent or attention-based models (e.g., [ HCRN , PSAC , FCNLSTM ] ), and dialog-style AV understanding leverages temporal context as well [ AVSD ] . AVQA systems often integrate temporal selection with spatial grounding and question-aware fusion for end-to-end reasoning [ MUSIC-AVQA ] . Overall, inter-modal attention is typically stacked in the aforementioned works (at least two layers). Notably, QA-TIGER [ QATIGER ] , the state-of-the-art method at the time of writing, uses four cross-attention blocks which are sequentially connected. 3 Method Figure 2 : Overall architecture of Q-TriM . First, question-guided token filtering keeps only the top tokens most relevant to the text and drops the rest. Next, Question-aware modality mixture computes four paths: TMA(Text,Audio,Video), TMA(Text,Video,Audio), CA(Text,Video,Video), and CA(Text,Audio,Audio). TMA stands for Tri-modal attention, and CA stands for cross-attention. Then question-conditioned weights are applied to the outputs. Finally, fused-feature reasoning combines these outputs and feeds the result to a classification layer to produce the answer. Q-TriM adopts a shallow and parallel architecture that combines cross-attention with Tri-Modal attention, instead of stacking attention blocks deeply. An overview of the architecture is shown in Figure 2 . Notations. A vector 𝐯 \\mathbf{v} is defined as a row vector by default. The dot-product between vectors 𝐮 \\mathbf{u} and 𝐯 \\mathbf{v} is thus 𝐮𝐯 ⊤ \\mathbf{u}\\mathbf{v}^{\\top} . A matrix 𝐗 = { 𝐱 i } i = 1 N ∈ ℝ N × D \\mathbf{X}=\\{\\mathbf{x}_{i}\\}_{i=1}^{N}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N\\times D} can be viewed as having N N rows of D D -dimensional vectors 𝐱 i \\mathbf{x}_{i} , i = 1 , … , N i=1,\\dots,N . Define the conventional dot-product attention for representations 𝐐 , 𝐊 , 𝐕 \\mathbf{Q},\\mathbf{K},\\mathbf{V} of proper dimensions 1 1 1 The attention originally contains normalization in the softmax, e.g., Q 