{R}^{5\\times D} Next, we apply a self-attention block to allow global interaction among all results: 𝐅 = SA ​ ( 𝐇 , 𝐇 , 𝐇 ) ∈ ℝ 5 × D \\mathbf{F}\\;=\\;\\mathrm{SA}\\!\\left(\\mathbf{H},\\,\\mathbf{H},\\,\\mathbf{H}\\right)\\in\\mathbb{R}^{5\\times D} Finally, the result passes through a classification layer to produce the answer: 𝐲 ^ = CLS ​ ( 𝐅 ) ∈ ℝ C \\hat{\\mathbf{y}}\\;=\\;\\text{CLS}(\\mathbf{F})\\;\\in\\;\\mathbb{R}^{C} where CLS denotes the classifier layer and C C denotes the number of classes. The model is trained by mi", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "fe91c1aa-1096-44fe-b2c2-7417150f2858", "uuid": "f60348ba-4bcf-4a3c-9a16-95a6ba7b3814", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T10:02:02.315Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "i , j | 𝐭 ) = exp ⁡ ( s ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) ) ∑ i ′ ∑ j ′ exp ⁡ ( s ​ ( i ′ , j ′ | 𝐭 ) ) \\displaystyle P_{\\mathbf{S}}(i,j|\\mathbf{t})=\\dfrac{\\exp(s(i,j|\\mathbf{t}))}{\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}\\sum_{j^{\\prime}}\\exp(s(i^{\\prime},j^{\\prime}|\\mathbf{t}))} (3) Thus, P 𝐒 ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) P_{\\mathbf{S}}(i,j|\\mathbf{t}) can be considered as a relative probability mass (weight) encoding the importance of i i -th video and j j -th audio frame conditional on question 𝐭 \\mathbf{t} . We consider three types of CSS s ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) s(i,j|\\mathbf{t}) as follows. 1) Default CSS. Let 𝐕 = { 𝐯 k } k = 1 T \\mathbf{V}=\\{\\mathbf{v}_{k}\\}_{k=1}^{T} and 𝐀 = { 𝐚 k } k = 1 T \\mathbf{A}=\\{\\mathbf{a}_{k}\\}_{k=1}^{T} be T × D T\\times D matrices of video and audio representations respectively. The first CSS s ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) s(i,j|\\mathbf{t}) for i i -th video and j j -th audio frames is defined as s ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) = 𝐯 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ + 𝐚 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ \\displaystyle s(i,j|\\mathbf{t})=\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}+\\mathbf{a}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top} (4) The CSS is a combination of the similarity between 𝐯 i \\mathbf{v}_{i} and query 𝐭 \\mathbf{t} and the similarity between 𝐚 j \\mathbf{a}_{j} and query 𝐭 \\mathbf{t} . We derive the video embedding as the weighted sum with respect to the distribution P 𝐒 ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) P_{\\mathbf{S}}(i,j|\\mathbf{t}) . Equivalently, it can be considered as a conditional expectation : 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐕 | 𝐭 ] := ∑ i , j P 𝐒 ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) ⋅ 𝐯 i \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}\\left[\\mathbf{V}|\\mathbf{t}\\right]:=\\sum_{i,j}P_{\\mathbf{S}}(i,j|\\mathbf{t})\\cdot\\mathbf{v}_{i} (5) We have that 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐕 | 𝐭 ] = Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐕 ) \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}\\left[\\mathbf{V}|\\mathbf{t}\\right]=\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{V}) (6) because 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐕 | 𝐭 ] = ∑ i , j 𝐯 i ⋅ P 𝐒 ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}\\left[\\mathbf{V}|\\mathbf{t}\\right]=\\sum_{i,j}\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\cdot P_{\\mathbf{S}}(i,j|\\mathbf{t}) (7) = ∑ i , j 𝐯 i ​ exp ⁡ ( 𝐯 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ + 𝐚 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ∑ i ′ ∑ j ′ exp ⁡ ( 𝐯 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ + 𝐚 j ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) \\displaystyle=\\sum_{i,j}\\dfrac{\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\exp(\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}+\\mathbf{a}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})}{\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}\\sum_{j^{\\prime}}\\exp(\\mathbf{v}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}+\\mathbf{a}_{j^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})} (8) = ∑ i 𝐯 i ​ exp ⁡ ( 𝐯 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ⋅ ∑ j exp ⁡ ( 𝐚 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ∑ i ′ exp ⁡ ( 𝐯 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ⋅ ∑ j ′ exp ⁡ ( 𝐚 j ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) \\displaystyle=\\dfrac{\\sum_{i}\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\exp(\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})\\cdot\\sum_{j}\\exp(\\mathbf{a}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})}{\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}\\exp(\\mathbf{v}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})\\cdot\\sum_{j^{\\prime}}\\exp(\\mathbf{a}_{j^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})} (9) = ∑ i 𝐯 i ⋅ exp ⁡ ( 𝐯 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ∑ i ′ exp ⁡ ( 𝐯 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) = Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐕 ) \\displaystyle=\\sum_{i}\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\cdot\\dfrac{\\exp(\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})}{\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}\\exp(\\mathbf{v}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})}=\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{V}) (10) Similarly, we can show 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐀 | 𝐭 ] = Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐀 ) \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}\\left[\\mathbf{A}|\\mathbf{t}\\right]=\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{A}) (11) Thus, with CSS given by ( 4 ), we obtain the conventional cross attention for video and audio with input text given by ( 6 ) and ( 11 ). 2) Cross-Reference CSS. The second type of CSS is s ¯ ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) = 𝐚 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ + 𝐯 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ \\displaystyle\\bar{s}(i,j|\\mathbf{t})=\\mathbf{a}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}+\\mathbf{v}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top} (12) Importantly, we use i i -th audio frame 𝐚 i \\mathbf{a}_{i} to represent the i i -th video frame for similarity score. Similarly, we use j j -th video frame 𝐯 j \\mathbf{v}_{j} to represent j j -th audio frame. The intuition is that, audio-visual questions are likely to address the co-occurrence of video and audio events [ videoaudio , videoaudio2 ] . If the i i -th frame contains an important clue to the audio-visual question, both the video and audio information at the i i -th frame will be important. In that case, the video information at i i -th frame can be closely related to i i -th audio 𝐚 i \\mathbf{a}_{i} given query 𝐭 \\mathbf{t} . The CSS matrix for ( 12 ) is simply the transpose of CSS matrix 𝐒 \\mathbf{S} in ( 2 ), because s ¯ ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) = s ​ ( j , i | 𝐭 ) \\bar{s}(i,j|\\mathbf{t})=s(j,i|\\mathbf{t}) . Thus, we will denote its CSS matrix by 𝐒 ⊤ \\mathbf{S}^{\\top} . We obtain the softmax distribution by applying 2D-softmax to 𝐒 ⊤ \\mathbf{S}^{\\top} given by P 𝐒 ⊤ {P_{\\mathbf{S}^{\\top}}} . The expected representations of video and audio under this distribution can be derived similarly to ( 10 ): 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐕 | 𝐭 ] = Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐕 ) \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}\\left[\\mathbf{V}|\\mathbf{t}\\right]=\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{V}) (13) and 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐀 | 𝐭 ] = Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐀 ) \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}\\left[\\mathbf{A}|\\mathbf{t}\\right]=\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{A}) (14) The attentions in ( 13 ) and ( 14 ) may appear somewhat unconventional; three different modalities are input to Q Q , K K and V V connections of the attention function. However, we can interpret ( 13 ) as follows. The attention weights are derived from text and audio ( 𝐭 \\mathbf{t} and 𝐀 \\mathbf{A} are connected to Q Q and K K of the attention function). The weights “select” important audio frames given the question. These weights are used to combine video frames. Thus, Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐕 ) \\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{V}) is a combination of video frames where the frames are considered important from the perspective of audio and text. We can expect these representations are useful for audio-visual queries. We call ( 13 ) and ( 14 ) Tri-Modal attention. 3) Mixed CSS. The third type of CSS we use is s ^ ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) = max ⁡ ( 𝐯 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ + 𝐚 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ , 𝐚 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ + 𝐯 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) \\displaystyle\\hat{s}(i,j|\\mathbf{t})=\\max(\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}+\\mathbf{a}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top},\\mathbf{a}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}+\\mathbf{v}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}) (15) ( 15 ) can be considered as mixing the previous CSSs ( 4 ) and ( 12 ) by taking their maximum. We chose the max function for mixing scores due the following reasons. The max function is widely adopted to combine or pool feature scores, e.g., max pooling [ AlexNet ] (keeps the most salient activation) or maxout [ MAXOUT ] (outputs the maximum over multiple linear responses). In particular, the max function is effective for suppressing irrelevant noise. For example, suppose one of feature score is high (large positive number) and the other is low (large negative number). Then this feature is potentially important, similar to a neuron output with a high activation value. However, if we mix the scores using sum or product, the irrelevant score can affect the result. Thus, the max operation is good at suppressing such irrelevant noise. An issue with the max function is that it is not a smooth function. Instead, we use Log-Sum-Exp [ boyd2004convex ] as a smooth approximation of the max function: max ⁡ ( a , b ) ≈ log ⁡ ( exp ⁡ ( a ) + exp ⁡ ( b ) ) \\displaystyle\\max(a,b)\\approx\\log(\\exp(a)+\\exp(b)) (16) If we apply ( 16 ) to CSS ( 15 ) and compute the expectations of video and audio representations, we obtain the following (a derivation is provided in the Supplementary Materials): 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐕 | 𝐭 ] ≈ 1 2 ​ Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐕 ) + 1 2 ​ Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐕 ) \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}[\\mathbf{V}|\\mathbf{t}]\\approx\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{V})+\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{V}) (17) and 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐀 | 𝐭 ] ≈ 1 2 ​ Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐀 ) + 1 2 ​ Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐀 ) . \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}[\\mathbf{A}|\\mathbf{t}]\\approx\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{A})+\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{A}). (18) Interestingly, these approximate representations can be obtained from the mixture of softmax distributions derived from previous CSSs. For example, ( 17 ) is equal to ∑ i , j ( P 𝐒 ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) + P 𝐒 ⊤ ​ ( i , j | 𝐭 ) 2 ) ​ 𝐯 i \\sum_{i,j}\\left(\\frac{P_{\\mathbf{S}}(i,j|\\mathbf{t})+P_{\\mathbf{S}^{\\top}}(i,j|\\mathbf{t})}{2}\\right)\\mathbf{v}_{i} which means that ( 17 ) is the expectation with respect to the mixture of distributions P 𝐒 P_{\\mathbf{S}} and P 𝐒 ⊤ P_{\\mathbf{S}^{\\top}} . Implementation: Modality Mixture. We obtained representations which are cross attentions ( Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐕 ) \\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{V}) and Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐀 ) \\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{A}) in ( 6 ) and ( 11 )), Tri-Modal Attentions ( Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐕 ) \\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{V}) and Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐀 ) \\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{A}) in ( 13 ) and ( 14 )), and their mixtures (( 17 ) and ( 18 )). Thus, these attentions constitute the main components of the proposed framework for modality fusion. For practical implementation, we combine these representations as follows: (i) compute the mixture weights for the four attention representations; (ii) concatenate the weighted attention representations. The concatenated representation will be used for the final reasoning of the answer. This approach is consistent with our horizontal fusion of modalities; we compute four types of attentions directly from audio, video and text representations, and merge them in parallel without deep sequential stacking. Denote these cross- and Tri-Modal attention outputs by r 1 = Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 p , 𝐕 p ) r_{1}=\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V}^{p},\\mathbf{V}^{p}) , r 2 = Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐀 ) r_{2}=\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{A}) , r 3 = Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐕 p ) r_{3}=\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{V}^{p}) and r 4 = Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐀 ) r_{4}=\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{A}) , respectively. Note that we used patch-level representations of video ( 𝐕 p ) (\\mathbf{V}^{p}) for the Value input to the attentions to better exploit spatial information. The attention outputs are fused using text-dependent weights. A precise weighting scheme is described as follows. For stability of those features, we modulate attention keys and values by text using FiLM [ FILM ] : FiLM ​ ( X ; 𝐭 ) \\displaystyle\\mathrm{FiLM}(X;\\mathbf{t}) = X ⊙ γ ​ ( 𝐭 ) + β ​ ( 𝐭 ) \\displaystyle\\;=\\;X\\odot\\gamma(\\mathbf{t})+\\beta(\\mathbf{t}) γ ​ ( 𝐭 ) \\displaystyle\\gamma(\\mathbf{t}) = 𝟏 + W γ ​ 𝐭 , β ​ ( t ) = W β ​ 𝐭 , \\displaystyle=\\mathbf{1}+W_{\\gamma}\\mathbf{t},\\;\\;\\beta(t)=W_{\\beta}\\mathbf{t}, (zero-initialized so initially identity). For r 1 r_{1} , r 2 r_{2} , r 3 r_{3} , and r 4 r_{4} , we use K ′ = FiLM ​ ( K ; 𝐭 ) , V ′ = FiLM ​ ( V ; 𝐭 ) , K^{\\prime}=\\mathrm{FiLM}(K;\\mathbf{t}),\\qquad V^{\\prime}=\\mathrm{FiLM}(V;\\mathbf{t}), and apply attention with ( K ′ , V ′ ) (K^{\\prime},V^{\\prime}) in place of ( K , V ) (K,V) inside Attention Module. From t t we produce four scalars ( q 1 , q 2 , q 3 , q 4 ) = W g ​ 𝐭 + b g , g i = 1 + 1 2 ​ tanh ⁡ ( q i ) . (q_{1},q_{2},q_{3},q_{4})=W_{g}\\mathbf{t}+b_{g},\\qquad g_{i}\\;=\\;1+\\tfrac{1}{2}\\tanh(q_{i}). Each attention is gated by g i g_{i} : h i = g i ​ r i , i = 1 , … , 4 . h_{i}\\;=\\;g_{i}\\,r_{i},\\qquad i=1,\\dots,4. This approach allows the question 𝐭 \\mathbf{t} to determine how much each attention result r i r_{i} should matter by assigning weights g i g_{i} that control their contribution. 3.4 Reasoning For the reasoning of the answer, we begin with concatenating the text embedding and four gated attention representations: 𝐇 = [ 𝐭 ; h 1 ; h 2 ; h 3 ; h 4 ] ∈ ℝ 5 × D \\mathbf{H}\\;=\\;\\big[\\mathbf{t}\\;;\\;h_{1}\\;;\\;h_{2}\\;;\\;h_{3}\\;;\\;h_{4}\\,\\big]\\in\\mathbb{R}^{5\\times D} Next, we apply a self-attention block to allow global interaction among all results: 𝐅 = SA ​ ( 𝐇 , 𝐇 , 𝐇 ) ∈ ℝ 5 × D \\mathbf{F}\\;=\\;\\mathrm{SA}\\!\\left(\\mathbf{H},\\,\\mathbf{H},\\,\\mathbf{H}\\right)\\in\\mathbb{R}^{5\\times D} Finally, the result passes through a classification layer to produce the answer: 𝐲 ^ = CLS ​ ( 𝐅 ) ∈ ℝ C \\hat{\\mathbf{y}}\\;=\\;\\text{CLS}(\\mathbf{F})\\;\\in\\;\\mathbb{R}^{C} where CLS denotes the classifier layer and C C denotes the number of classes. The model is trained by mi", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1783418538045", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "chatcmpl-tool-8f2ebee6570119d7", "name": "Bash", "input": {"command": "python3 -c \"\nimport re\nwith open('/tmp/qtrim_full.html') as f:\n    html = f.read()\nhtml = re.sub(r'<script[^>]*>.*?</script>', '', html, flags=re.DOTALL)\nhtml = re.sub(r'<style[^>]*>.*?</style>', '', html, flags=re.DOTALL)\nhtml = re.sub(r'<[^>]+>', ' ', html)\nhtml = re.sub(r'&nbsp;', ' ', html)\nhtml = re.sub(r'&amp;', '&', html)\nhtml = re.sub(r'&lt;', '<', html)\nhtml = re.sub(r'&gt;', '>', html)\nhtml = re.sub(r'&quot;', '\\\"', html)\nhtml = re.sub(r'\\s+', ' ', html)\nprint(html[30000:42000])\n\"", "description": "Extract experiments section"}}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "fe91c1aa-1096-44fe-b2c2-7417150f2858", "uuid": "3fbad5f4-83bf-4297-a849-1f7848c06618"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8f2ebee6570119d7", "type": "tool_result", "content": "nimizing the cross-entropy between the predicted label 𝐲 ^ \\hat{\\mathbf{y}} and the ground-truth label 𝐲 \\mathbf{y} : ℒ CE = − ∑ c = 1 C y c ​ log ⁡ y ^ c . \\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{CE}}=-\\sum_{c=1}^{C}y_{c}\\log\\hat{y}_{c}\\,. (19) 4 Experiments 4.1 Datasets We evaluate on MUSIC-AVQA [ MUSIC-AVQA ] , MUSIC-AVQA-R [ MUSIC-AVQA-R ] , and MUSIC-AVQA-v2.0 [ MUSIC-AVQA-2.0 ] , adopting the official train/val/test splits as in Table 1 . The base MUSIC-AVQA [ MUSIC-AVQA ] provides a standard benchmark over 22 instruments with audio-only, visual-only, and audio-visual questions. MUSIC-AVQA-R [ MUSIC-AVQA-R ] builds on MUSIC-AVQA and upgrades the setting by concentrating on rare and out-of-distribution cases (e.g., uncommon instruments and atypical contexts), explicitly probing robustness beyond head-class priors and frequency-driven shortcuts. MUSIC-AVQA-v2.0 [ MUSIC-AVQA-2.0 ] upgrades the benchmark to address dataset biases by enriching ensemble and multi-instrument scenes, rebalancing question types (e.g., existence, location, temporal) across modalities. It provides paired bias-balanced evaluation splits, which enable controlled analysis of spurious correlations versus genuine cross-modal reasoning. Table 1 : Dataset statistics. Dataset Videos Train Valid QA Test QA MUSIC-AVQA 9,288 31,927 4,568 9,129 MUSIC-AVQA-R 9,288 – – 211,572 MUSIC-AVQA-v2.0 10,512 37,429 5,345 10,816 4.2 Implementation Details We extract common-space representations by using CLIP [ CLIP ] for video and text embeddings, and ImageBind [ imagebind ] for audio embeddings. Video frames are sampled every 2 seconds with the hidden size given by D = 1024 D=1024 , and we obtain one CLIP embedding per frame. However, this frame-wise CLIP encoding may not fully represent spatial information. Thus, we additionally extract CLIP-based patch-level embeddings for video: for each frame, P = 256 P=256 patch tokens with dimensionality 1280 1280 . All attention modules use 8 heads. Dropout 0.1 is applied to every attention module and to the final classification layer. Optimization uses AdamW [ adamw ] with a step scheduler that multiplies the learning rate by 0.1 {0.1} every 8 epochs. The loss employs label smoothing [ labelsmoothing ] 0.1 0.1 . We apply gradient clipping of 0.1 0.1 (global norm). Training is performed on a single NVIDIA A6000 GPU. 4.3 Quantitative Results and Analysis MUSIC-AVQA-R. On the debiased MUSIC-AVQA-R [ MUSIC-AVQA-R ] benchmark, our model attains 70.89% overall as in Table 3 . It performs strongly on both frequent (Head) and rare (Tail) answer categories, e.g., Audio QA Count (H/T: 85.68/76.12%) and Visual QA Local (H/T: 89.45/78.95%). For Audio-Visual QA, Count (H/T: 81.43/44.21%) and Local (H/T: 66.27/63.51%) remain competitive, suggesting robust question-conditioned temporal–spatial reasoning even under long-tail distributions. MUSIC-AVQA. Our model achieves an overall accuracy of 77.68% on the MUSIC-AVQA [ MUSIC-AVQA ] test set, surpassing prior work such as QA-TIGER (77.62%) as shown in Table 3 . By modality, we obtain a strong Visual QA average of 85.76% (Count 84.46%, Local 87.02%) and an Audio-Visual QA average of 73.78% (Exist 82.29%, Count 80.87%, Local 71.85%, Comp 62.58%, Temp 69.83%). Audio QA averages 77.84%. MUSIC-AVQA-v2.0. We further evaluate on the MUSIC-AVQA-v2.0 [ MUSIC-AVQA-2.0 ] benchmark. When trained on the biased dataset, Q-TriM achieves state-of-the-art performance on both the bias test (78.40%) and the balanced test (75.31%). When trained on the balanced dataset, it remains state-of-the-art performance on the bias test (76.92%), but on the balanced test it falls short by a small margin (76.29%), as shown in Table 4 . Overall, Q-TriM attains strong results across all three benchmarks. This suggests that adopting a shallow and parallel design, rather than deep and sequential, for inter-modal attention can be effective for learning cross-modal interactions compared to deeper stacked architectures as in baseline methods. Table 2 : Experimental results (%) on the MUSIC-AVQA-R test set, with H and T representing performance on Head (frequent) and Tail (rare) answer categories, respectively. Bold denotes the best performance, and underline indicates the second-best performance. Method Audio QA Visual QA Audio-Visual QA Avg Count Comp Count Local Exist Count Local Comp Temp H T H T H T H T H T H T H T H T H T FCNLSTM [ FCNLSTM ] 66.23 36.48 64.78 51.24 61.75 5.31 54.86 51.06 64.76 78.52 62.69 7.23 46.66 57.30 43.13 71.67 37.02 30.78 54.12 BiLSTM [ BILSTM ] 73.68 46.32 21.51 77.58 64.30 0.00 53.92 42.01 87.51 21.14 62.85 2.18 35.16 43.75 27.61 74.38 17.58 31.32 48.84 HCAttn [ HCAttn ] 61.67 41.63 59.09 47.14 56.52 9.20 67.01 53.16 66.57 61.13 59.53 12.48 37.05 42.48 48.81 60.12 33.82 39.26 51.90 MCAN [ MCAN ] 75.02 60.16 58.89 50.90 64.58 26.69 66.62 65.25 61.29 67.29 64.76 25.28 46.11 61.61 50.57 52.04 34.64 58.05 57.27 PSAC [ PSAC ] 53.01 56.68 57.41 48.12 49.55 26.43 72.96 60.69 50.56 55.54 56.70 19.58 41.98 52.30 38.13 58.92 26.68 46.24 50.45 HME [ HME ] 62.60 53.95 54.97 58.29 50.95 16.46 73.25 58.06 65.74 66.49 63.18 17.18 39.59 45.03 53.20 69.57 39.35 41.57 53.66 HCRN [ HCRN ] 55.53 53.31 47.17 32.44 41.87 23.55 39.40 51.27 41.81 65.45 54.58 19.57 36.62 42.72 33.33 36.87 40.47 44.13 43.92 AVSD [ AVSD ] 54.00 47.84 60.61 47.79 63.25 10.07 74.70 61.43 66.28 61.98 42.61 18.06 33.00 40.35 51.98 66.00 40.14 41.52 52.33 Pano-AVQA [ PANO-AVQA ] 50.57 43.45 50.78 43.64 47.28 15.50 76.19 65.51 52.37 22.04 52.21 21.52 44.35 61.69 45.61 40.49 40.05 39.43 47.40 ST-AVQA [ MUSIC-AVQA ] 56.40 41.48 62.22 55.79 59.86 12.94 63.31 54.00 49.78 56.41 38.11 19.41 35.05 44.09 53.30 62.44 40.42 35.85 52.80 LAVISH [ LAVISH ] 61.73 43.99 66.00 50.38 55.33 10.21 70.71 68.78 77.83 79.46 49.38 14.47 41.76 41.01 59.26 65.10 41.84 46.26 57.63 TSPM [ TSPM ] 81.65 71.80 67.6