{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b51923a8410ade48", "type": "tool_result", "content": " are provided in the Supplementary Materials. Table 6 : Evaluation of token filtering with varying keep ratios on MUSIC-AVQA-R. Consistent with prior findings, a keep ratio of 0.5 0.5 achieves the highest accuracy. Keep Ratio A-QA V-QA AV-QA Avg 0.1 75.28 82.60 61.79 70.11 0.3 75.30 83.05 62.37 70.56 0.5(ours) 74.74 83.64 62.85 70.89 0.7 74.28 82.71 62.56 70.39 0.9 75.35 83.22 62.15 70.50 5 Conclusion We introduce Q-TriM, an AVQA model that replaces deeply stacked attention with a shallow, parallel inter-modal and question-aware fusion. The pipeline consists of three stages. First, we apply token filtering to retain only the semantically meaningful patches that are relevant to the given question. Next, Tri-Modal Attention and cross attention are applied in parallel to obtain text-relevant video and audio representations. Finally, a modality mixture head aggregates features with question-aware weights, yielding a compact representation that emphasizes information most pertinent to the query. Q-TriM attains state-of-the-art performance on three benchmark datasets. Especially, we demonstrate the robustness of our model by achieving a substantial performance margin over prior state-of-the-art methods on the MUSIC-AVQA-R dataset. As a direction for future work, we plan to explore various CSS scores in the proposed attention framework and extend them to various multi-modal tasks. Acknowledgements This work was partly supported by the Institute of Information & Communications Technology Planning & Evaluation (IITP) grant funded by the Korea government (MSIT) (IITP-2026-RS-2020-II201819, ICT Creative Consilience Program, 10%, and No.RS-2026-25507543, Development of AI Co-Scientist based on Scientific Causal World Model, 80%) and by the National Research Foundation of Korea (NRF) grant funded by the Korea government(MSIT)(RS-2022-NR070834,RS-2026-25482946). References Audio-Visual Question Answering Supplementary Material F Derivation of Eq. (17) and Eq. (18) We derive Eq. (17) and Eq. (18) by applying the Log-Sum-Exp approximation in Eq. (16) to the mixed CSS given in Eq. (15). We first derive the approximation for 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐕 ∣ 𝐭 ] \\mathbb{E}[\\mathbf{V}\\mid\\mathbf{t}] as follows. 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐕 ∣ 𝐭 ] \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}\\left[\\mathbf{V}\\mid\\mathbf{t}\\right] = ∑ i , j 𝐯 i ⋅ P 𝐒 ​ ( i , j ∣ 𝐭 ) \\displaystyle=\\sum_{i,j}\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\cdot P_{\\mathbf{S}}(i,j\\mid\\mathbf{t}) (20) ≈ ∑ i , j 𝐯 i ​ e 𝐯 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ​ e 𝐚 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ + e 𝐚 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ​ e 𝐯 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ∑ i ′ , j ′ ( e 𝐯 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ​ e 𝐚 j ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ + e 𝐚 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ​ e 𝐯 j ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) \\displaystyle\\approx\\sum_{i,j}\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\,\\frac{e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}+e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}}{\\sum_{i^{\\prime},j^{\\prime}}\\left(e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{j^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}+e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{j^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}\\right)} (21) = ( ∑ i 𝐯 i ​ e 𝐯 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ​ ( ∑ j e 𝐚 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) + ( ∑ i 𝐯 i ​ e 𝐚 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ​ ( ∑ j e 𝐯 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ( ∑ i ′ e 𝐯 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ​ ( ∑ j ′ e 𝐚 j ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) + ( ∑ i ′ e 𝐚 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ​ ( ∑ j ′ e 𝐯 j ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) \\displaystyle=\\frac{(\\sum_{i}\\mathbf{v}_{i}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})(\\sum_{j}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})+(\\sum_{i}\\mathbf{v}_{i}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})(\\sum_{j}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})}{(\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})(\\sum_{j^{\\prime}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{j^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})+(\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})(\\sum_{j^{\\prime}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{j^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})} (22) The two terms in the denominator of Eq. (22) are identical products. Thus, the denominator becomes 2 ​ ∑ i ′ e 𝐯 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ⋅ ∑ j ′ e 𝐚 j ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ . \\displaystyle 2\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}\\cdot\\sum_{j^{\\prime}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{j^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}. (23) Substituting Eq. (23) into Eq. (22) yields 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐕 ∣ 𝐭 ] \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}[\\mathbf{V}\\mid\\mathbf{t}] ≈ 1 2 ​ ∑ i 𝐯 i ​ exp ⁡ ( 𝐯 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ∑ i ′ exp ⁡ ( 𝐯 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) + 1 2 ​ ∑ i 𝐯 i ​ exp ⁡ ( 𝐚 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ∑ i ′ exp ⁡ ( 𝐚 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) \\displaystyle\\approx\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\frac{\\sum_{i}\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\exp(\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})}{\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}\\exp(\\mathbf{v}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})}+\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\frac{\\sum_{i}\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\exp(\\mathbf{a}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})}{\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}\\exp(\\mathbf{a}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})} (24) = 1 2 ​ Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐕 ) + 1 2 ​ Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐕 ) . \\displaystyle=\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{V})+\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{V}). (25) Similarly, we obtain 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐀 ∣ 𝐭 ] ≈ 1 2 ​ Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐀 ) + 1 2 ​ Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐀 ) . \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}[\\mathbf{A}\\mid\\mathbf{t}]\\approx\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{A})+\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{A}). (26) G Algorithm A detailed description of Q-TriM is given in Algorithm 1 . Input: Frame-level video embeddings 𝐕 = { 𝐯 t } t = 1 T \\mathbf{V}=\\{\\mathbf{v}_{t}\\}_{t=1}^{T} , patch-level video tokens 𝐕 p = { 𝐯 t p } t = 1 T \\mathbf{V}^{p}=\\{\\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t}\\}_{t=1}^{T} , audio embeddings 𝐀 = { 𝐚 t } t = 1 T \\mathbf{A}=\\{\\mathbf{a}_{t}\\}_{t=1}^{T} , question embedding 𝐭 \\mathbf{t} , keep ratio k k , number of patches P P Output: Answer logits 𝐲 ^ ∈ ℝ C \\hat{\\mathbf{y}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{C} 1. Token Filtering K ← k ​ P K\\leftarrow kP for t = 1 t=1 to T T do 𝐯 t p ← \\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t}\\leftarrow Top- K K selection of 𝐯 t p \\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t} end for 2. Self-Attention Refinement 𝐯 t p ← Attn ​ ( 𝐯 t p , 𝐯 t p , 𝐯 t p ) \\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t},\\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t},\\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t}) 𝐯 t ← Attn ​ ( 𝐯 t , 𝐯 t , 𝐯 t ) \\mathbf{v}_{t}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{v}_{t},\\mathbf{v}_{t},\\mathbf{v}_{t}) 𝐚 t ← Attn ​ ( 𝐚 t , 𝐚 t , 𝐚 t ) \\mathbf{a}_{t}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{a}_{t},\\mathbf{a}_{t},\\mathbf{a}_{t}) 𝐭 ← Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐭 , 𝐭 ) \\mathbf{t}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{t}) 3. Tri-Modal Attention and Cross Attention 𝐫 1 ← Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 p , 𝐕 p ) \\mathbf{r}_{1}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V}^{p},\\mathbf{V}^{p}) 𝐫 2 ← Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐀 ) \\mathbf{r}_{2}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{A}) 𝐫 3 ← Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐕 p ) \\mathbf{r}_{3}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{V}^{p}) 𝐫 4 ← Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐀 ) \\mathbf{r}_{4}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{A}) 4. Gating 𝐪 ← W g ​ 𝐭 + 𝐛 g \\mathbf{q}\\leftarrow W_{g}\\mathbf{t}+\\mathbf{b}_{g} , g i ← 1 + 1 2 ​ tanh ⁡ ( q i ) g_{i}\\leftarrow 1+\\tfrac{1}{2}\\tanh(q_{i}) 𝐡 i ← g i ​ 𝐫 i , i = 1 , … , 4 \\mathbf{h}_{i}\\leftarrow g_{i}\\,\\mathbf{r}_{i},\\quad i=1,\\dots,4 5. Reasoning 𝐇 ← [ 𝐭 ; 𝐡 1 ; 𝐡 2 ; 𝐡 3 ; 𝐡 4 ] ∈ ℝ 5 × D \\mathbf{H}\\leftarrow[\\,\\mathbf{t};\\,\\mathbf{h}_{1};\\,\\mathbf{h}_{2};\\,\\mathbf{h}_{3};\\,\\mathbf{h}_{4}\\,]\\in\\mathbb{R}^{5\\times D} 𝐅 ← Attn ​ ( 𝐇 , 𝐇 , 𝐇 ) \\mathbf{F}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{H},\\mathbf{H},\\mathbf{H}) 𝐲 ^ ← classification layer ​ ( 𝐅 ) ∈ ℝ C \\hat{\\mathbf{y}}\\leftarrow\\text{classification layer}(\\mathbf{F})\\in\\mathbb{R}^{C} return 𝐲 ^ \\hat{\\mathbf{y}} Algorithm 1 Q-TriM H Additional Ablation Study We provide an additional ablation study on the MUSIC-AVQA dataset [ MUSIC-AVQA ] . Table 7 shows the results. We observe a trend similar to that on MUSIC-AVQA-R [ MUSIC-AVQA-R ] : each component of Q-TriM contributes to the overall performance. Table 7 : Ablation study of Q-TriM on MUSIC-AVQA dataset [ MUSIC-AVQA ] . Method A-QA V-QA AV-QA Avg w/o All Modules (Base) 73.56 84.23 70.86 74.88 w/o Token Filtering 76.60 82.58 71.94 75.58 w/o Tri-Modal Attention 76.78 82.78 71.47 75.41 w/o Tri-Modal Attention (replace with cross attention) 78.40 84.72 72.00 76.50 w/o Modality Mixture 74.55 82.62 71.55 75.01 Ours 77.84 85.76 73.78 77.68 I Qualitative Analysis of Token Filtering To verify the effectiveness of the token filtering module, we visualize input frames before and after token filtering. The question is: \"What kind of musical instrument is it?\" For three different examples, we show the masked outputs. As shown in Figures 3 – 5 , the regions corresponding to musical instruments are more likely to remain after filtering, while potentially irrelevant regions are masked out. This indicates that the token filtering module preserves informative tokens relevant to the question. (a) Before filtering (b) After filtering Figure 3 : Visualization of token filtering for Example 1. For the question \"What kind of musical instrument is it?\" , the regions corresponding to the flute and violin are mostly preserved, whereas potentially irrelevant regions are masked out. (a) Before filtering (b) After filtering Figure 4 : Visualization of token filtering for Example 2. (a) Before filtering (b) After filtering Figure 5 : Visualization of token filtering for Example 3. J Adaptive keep-ratio in token filtering In general, it is difficult to make K K directly learnable/adaptive in top- K K selection operator for token filtering, because the hard top- K K operation is non-differentiable preventing the gradient flow to K K . Instead, we adopt the workaround proposed in [ KEEPRATIO ] that uses soft top- K K selection. Specifically, we adjust the temperature parameter in the softmax approximating hard max- K K as follows. Let 𝐬 t ∈ ℝ P \\mathbf{s}_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{P} denote the token scores at frame t t , where P P is the number of patch tokens. We define the soft assignment over tokens as 𝐰 t = softmax ​ ( 𝐬 t τ ) . \\mathbf{w}_{t}=\\mathrm{softmax}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\mathbf{s}_{t}}{\\tau}\\right). Here, the temperature parameter τ \\tau controls the sharpness of the distribution. When τ \\tau is small, the softmax becomes sharper and places most of its mass on a few high-score tokens; when τ \\tau is large, the distribution becomes smoother and gr", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "fe91c1aa-1096-44fe-b2c2-7417150f2858", "uuid": "7539b04b-0e2c-4b31-9546-cd8e02d2f25c", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T10:02:44.068Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": " are provided in the Supplementary Materials. Table 6 : Evaluation of token filtering with varying keep ratios on MUSIC-AVQA-R. Consistent with prior findings, a keep ratio of 0.5 0.5 achieves the highest accuracy. Keep Ratio A-QA V-QA AV-QA Avg 0.1 75.28 82.60 61.79 70.11 0.3 75.30 83.05 62.37 70.56 0.5(ours) 74.74 83.64 62.85 70.89 0.7 74.28 82.71 62.56 70.39 0.9 75.35 83.22 62.15 70.50 5 Conclusion We introduce Q-TriM, an AVQA model that replaces deeply stacked attention with a shallow, parallel inter-modal and question-aware fusion. The pipeline consists of three stages. First, we apply token filtering to retain only the semantically meaningful patches that are relevant to the given question. Next, Tri-Modal Attention and cross attention are applied in parallel to obtain text-relevant video and audio representations. Finally, a modality mixture head aggregates features with question-aware weights, yielding a compact representation that emphasizes information most pertinent to the query. Q-TriM attains state-of-the-art performance on three benchmark datasets. Especially, we demonstrate the robustness of our model by achieving a substantial performance margin over prior state-of-the-art methods on the MUSIC-AVQA-R dataset. As a direction for future work, we plan to explore various CSS scores in the proposed attention framework and extend them to various multi-modal tasks. Acknowledgements This work was partly supported by the Institute of Information & Communications Technology Planning & Evaluation (IITP) grant funded by the Korea government (MSIT) (IITP-2026-RS-2020-II201819, ICT Creative Consilience Program, 10%, and No.RS-2026-25507543, Development of AI Co-Scientist based on Scientific Causal World Model, 80%) and by the National Research Foundation of Korea (NRF) grant funded by the Korea government(MSIT)(RS-2022-NR070834,RS-2026-25482946). References Audio-Visual Question Answering Supplementary Material F Derivation of Eq. (17) and Eq. (18) We derive Eq. (17) and Eq. (18) by applying the Log-Sum-Exp approximation in Eq. (16) to the mixed CSS given in Eq. (15). We first derive the approximation for 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐕 ∣ 𝐭 ] \\mathbb{E}[\\mathbf{V}\\mid\\mathbf{t}] as follows. 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐕 ∣ 𝐭 ] \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}\\left[\\mathbf{V}\\mid\\mathbf{t}\\right] = ∑ i , j 𝐯 i ⋅ P 𝐒 ​ ( i , j ∣ 𝐭 ) \\displaystyle=\\sum_{i,j}\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\cdot P_{\\mathbf{S}}(i,j\\mid\\mathbf{t}) (20) ≈ ∑ i , j 𝐯 i ​ e 𝐯 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ​ e 𝐚 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ + e 𝐚 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ​ e 𝐯 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ∑ i ′ , j ′ ( e 𝐯 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ​ e 𝐚 j ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ + e 𝐚 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ​ e 𝐯 j ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) \\displaystyle\\approx\\sum_{i,j}\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\,\\frac{e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}+e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}}{\\sum_{i^{\\prime},j^{\\prime}}\\left(e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{j^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}+e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{j^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}\\right)} (21) = ( ∑ i 𝐯 i ​ e 𝐯 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ​ ( ∑ j e 𝐚 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) + ( ∑ i 𝐯 i ​ e 𝐚 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ​ ( ∑ j e 𝐯 j ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ( ∑ i ′ e 𝐯 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ​ ( ∑ j ′ e 𝐚 j ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) + ( ∑ i ′ e 𝐚 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ​ ( ∑ j ′ e 𝐯 j ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) \\displaystyle=\\frac{(\\sum_{i}\\mathbf{v}_{i}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})(\\sum_{j}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})+(\\sum_{i}\\mathbf{v}_{i}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})(\\sum_{j}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{j}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})}{(\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})(\\sum_{j^{\\prime}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{j^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})+(\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})(\\sum_{j^{\\prime}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{j^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}})} (22) The two terms in the denominator of Eq. (22) are identical products. Thus, the denominator becomes 2 ​ ∑ i ′ e 𝐯 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ⋅ ∑ j ′ e 𝐚 j ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ . \\displaystyle 2\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{v}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}\\cdot\\sum_{j^{\\prime}}e^{\\,\\mathbf{a}_{j^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top}}. (23) Substituting Eq. (23) into Eq. (22) yields 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐕 ∣ 𝐭 ] \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}[\\mathbf{V}\\mid\\mathbf{t}] ≈ 1 2 ​ ∑ i 𝐯 i ​ exp ⁡ ( 𝐯 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ∑ i ′ exp ⁡ ( 𝐯 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) + 1 2 ​ ∑ i 𝐯 i ​ exp ⁡ ( 𝐚 i ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) ∑ i ′ exp ⁡ ( 𝐚 i ′ ​ 𝐭 ⊤ ) \\displaystyle\\approx\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\frac{\\sum_{i}\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\exp(\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})}{\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}\\exp(\\mathbf{v}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})}+\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\frac{\\sum_{i}\\mathbf{v}_{i}\\exp(\\mathbf{a}_{i}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})}{\\sum_{i^{\\prime}}\\exp(\\mathbf{a}_{i^{\\prime}}\\mathbf{t}^{\\top})} (24) = 1 2 ​ Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐕 ) + 1 2 ​ Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐕 ) . \\displaystyle=\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{V})+\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{V}). (25) Similarly, we obtain 𝔼 ​ [ 𝐀 ∣ 𝐭 ] ≈ 1 2 ​ Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐀 ) + 1 2 ​ Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐀 ) . \\displaystyle\\mathbb{E}[\\mathbf{A}\\mid\\mathbf{t}]\\approx\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{A})+\\tfrac{1}{2}\\,\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{A}). (26) G Algorithm A detailed description of Q-TriM is given in Algorithm 1 . Input: Frame-level video embeddings 𝐕 = { 𝐯 t } t = 1 T \\mathbf{V}=\\{\\mathbf{v}_{t}\\}_{t=1}^{T} , patch-level video tokens 𝐕 p = { 𝐯 t p } t = 1 T \\mathbf{V}^{p}=\\{\\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t}\\}_{t=1}^{T} , audio embeddings 𝐀 = { 𝐚 t } t = 1 T \\mathbf{A}=\\{\\mathbf{a}_{t}\\}_{t=1}^{T} , question embedding 𝐭 \\mathbf{t} , keep ratio k k , number of patches P P Output: Answer logits 𝐲 ^ ∈ ℝ C \\hat{\\mathbf{y}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{C} 1. Token Filtering K ← k ​ P K\\leftarrow kP for t = 1 t=1 to T T do 𝐯 t p ← \\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t}\\leftarrow Top- K K selection of 𝐯 t p \\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t} end for 2. Self-Attention Refinement 𝐯 t p ← Attn ​ ( 𝐯 t p , 𝐯 t p , 𝐯 t p ) \\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t},\\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t},\\mathbf{v}^{p}_{t}) 𝐯 t ← Attn ​ ( 𝐯 t , 𝐯 t , 𝐯 t ) \\mathbf{v}_{t}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{v}_{t},\\mathbf{v}_{t},\\mathbf{v}_{t}) 𝐚 t ← Attn ​ ( 𝐚 t , 𝐚 t , 𝐚 t ) \\mathbf{a}_{t}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{a}_{t},\\mathbf{a}_{t},\\mathbf{a}_{t}) 𝐭 ← Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐭 , 𝐭 ) \\mathbf{t}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{t}) 3. Tri-Modal Attention and Cross Attention 𝐫 1 ← Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 p , 𝐕 p ) \\mathbf{r}_{1}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V}^{p},\\mathbf{V}^{p}) 𝐫 2 ← Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐀 ) \\mathbf{r}_{2}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{A}) 𝐫 3 ← Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐀 , 𝐕 p ) \\mathbf{r}_{3}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{A},\\mathbf{V}^{p}) 𝐫 4 ← Attn ​ ( 𝐭 , 𝐕 , 𝐀 ) \\mathbf{r}_{4}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{t},\\mathbf{V},\\mathbf{A}) 4. Gating 𝐪 ← W g ​ 𝐭 + 𝐛 g \\mathbf{q}\\leftarrow W_{g}\\mathbf{t}+\\mathbf{b}_{g} , g i ← 1 + 1 2 ​ tanh ⁡ ( q i ) g_{i}\\leftarrow 1+\\tfrac{1}{2}\\tanh(q_{i}) 𝐡 i ← g i ​ 𝐫 i , i = 1 , … , 4 \\mathbf{h}_{i}\\leftarrow g_{i}\\,\\mathbf{r}_{i},\\quad i=1,\\dots,4 5. Reasoning 𝐇 ← [ 𝐭 ; 𝐡 1 ; 𝐡 2 ; 𝐡 3 ; 𝐡 4 ] ∈ ℝ 5 × D \\mathbf{H}\\leftarrow[\\,\\mathbf{t};\\,\\mathbf{h}_{1};\\,\\mathbf{h}_{2};\\,\\mathbf{h}_{3};\\,\\mathbf{h}_{4}\\,]\\in\\mathbb{R}^{5\\times D} 𝐅 ← Attn ​ ( 𝐇 , 𝐇 , 𝐇 ) \\mathbf{F}\\leftarrow\\text{Attn}(\\mathbf{H},\\mathbf{H},\\mathbf{H}) 𝐲 ^ ← classification layer ​ ( 𝐅 ) ∈ ℝ C \\hat{\\mathbf{y}}\\leftarrow\\text{classification layer}(\\mathbf{F})\\in\\mathbb{R}^{C} return 𝐲 ^ \\hat{\\mathbf{y}} Algorithm 1 Q-TriM H Additional Ablation Study We provide an additional ablation study on the MUSIC-AVQA dataset [ MUSIC-AVQA ] . Table 7 shows the results. We observe a trend similar to that on MUSIC-AVQA-R [ MUSIC-AVQA-R ] : each component of Q-TriM contributes to the overall performance. Table 7 : Ablation study of Q-TriM on MUSIC-AVQA dataset [ MUSIC-AVQA ] . Method A-QA V-QA AV-QA Avg w/o All Modules (Base) 73.56 84.23 70.86 74.88 w/o Token Filtering 76.60 82.58 71.94 75.58 w/o Tri-Modal Attention 76.78 82.78 71.47 75.41 w/o Tri-Modal Attention (replace with cross attention) 78.40 84.72 72.00 76.50 w/o Modality Mixture 74.55 82.62 71.55 75.01 Ours 77.84 85.76 73.78 77.68 I Qualitative Analysis of Token Filtering To verify the effectiveness of the token filtering module, we visualize input frames before and after token filtering. The question is: \"What kind of musical instrument is it?\" For three different examples, we show the masked outputs. As shown in Figures 3 – 5 , the regions corresponding to musical instruments are more likely to remain after filtering, while potentially irrelevant regions are masked out. This indicates that the token filtering module preserves informative tokens relevant to the question. (a) Before filtering (b) After filtering Figure 3 : Visualization of token filtering for Example 1. For the question \"What kind of musical instrument is it?\" , the regions corresponding to the flute and violin are mostly preserved, whereas potentially irrelevant regions are masked out. (a) Before filtering (b) After filtering Figure 4 : Visualization of token filtering for Example 2. (a) Before filtering (b) After filtering Figure 5 : Visual